{
  "text": "The grid [CITATION_1] n contains large \"cliques\": sets of points in which any two are collinear. In such a clique, the number of monochromatic pairs is least when the colors are balanced, and even then is close to 1 2 . Thus, we expect that for at least some lengths k, q(k) > 1 2 \u2212 \u01eb for some \u01eb that goes to 0 with n. This intuition is correct in a way that we will make more precise.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "54088935"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "54088935": {
      "title": "Regularity and positional games",
      "abstract": "1.Introduction. Suppose X is a set, \ud835\udc9e a collection of sets (usually subsets of X), and N is cardinal number. Following the terminology of Rado [1], we say \ud835\udc9e is N-regular in X if,for any partition of X into N parts, some part has as a subset a member of \ud835\udc9e. if \ud835\udc9e is n-regular in X for each integer n, we say \ud835\udc9e is regular in X."
    }
  }
}